WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.320
We always talk about CAR-T versus bispecifics, and in reality, it's both.

00:00:04.420 --> 00:00:05.140
We use both.

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:09.400
But the comparisons are always, well, CAR-T is hard, and it is.

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:13.200
I mean, I want to die most days by the end of the day because of all the manufacturing

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:17.440
issues we've had, all of the out-of-spec.

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:18.920
I mean, there's so many things that can happen.

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:20.680
And again, the access, right?

00:00:20.700 --> 00:00:23.760
The number one issue with these therapies, especially CAR-T, is access.

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:29.360
And if you can just give the actual gene therapy to that patient, and you can figure out a

00:00:29.360 --> 00:00:35.160
way to make the T-cells in that person without having any manufacturing, not needing lymphodepletion,

00:00:35.620 --> 00:00:37.140
that could actually change everything.

00:00:37.380 --> 00:00:39.720
So I think this is really exciting.

00:00:39.940 --> 00:00:43.780
There's actually other CARs that have already been tested as well.

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:48.340
There's a paper in Lancet with a different in vivo BCMA CAR last June.

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:53.580
And so again, brand new data with like four patients each.

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:57.180
So there's not, you know, I don't have a lot of clinical data for you, but lots to think

00:00:57.180 --> 00:00:58.880
about how this is going to go in the future.

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:04.540
So again, differences with ex vivo CAR-T versus truly in vivo, it really eliminates all these,

00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:09.420
you know, things like pre-conditioning lymphodepletion, the logistics become so much easier.

00:01:09.980 --> 00:01:11.340
The culture doesn't need to be there.

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:14.540
All these things that can happen when those cells are in culture goes out the window.

00:01:15.140 --> 00:01:18.980
There's other things that can happen, which is my last slide, but reduced cost of goods

00:01:18.980 --> 00:01:19.680
and manufacturing.

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:21.060
We talk about price, right?

00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:24.080
And so again, this could actually really change all of that.

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:26.060
So this was a Kaelin.

00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:27.500
I have nothing to do with this study.

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:28.660
This was done in Australia.

00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:29.140
And Dr.

00:01:29.200 --> 00:01:29.340
Joy, you're welcome.

00:01:29.340 --> 00:01:32.960
Dr. Joy Ho presented it as a late breaking, which I was really excited about because it's

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:36.360
CAR-T, but I was also surprised because it was for patients, but I was still excited

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:38.860
that we had two late breaking at ASH for myeloma.

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:43.960
So again, this is a modified LVB generating anti-BCMA CAR-T cell.

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:49.000
So there's an envelope modified LVV in terms of the viral vector, the lentiviral vector.

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:52.000
There's a detargeted VSVG.

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:55.520
I don't know everything about this stuff, the physogen, but this really helps.

00:01:56.220 --> 00:01:59.300
The biggest question is how do you get this to T cells, right?

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:01.120
Inside your body, not go to other organs.

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:06.500
And so again, this is sort of how they were able to use ways to avoid things like the

00:02:06.500 --> 00:02:06.700
liver.

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:09.540
So again, T cell redirecting, because you have the CD3 SCFE.

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:12.540
And then again, they went after BCMA as the antigen.

00:02:12.700 --> 00:02:16.800
So there's a lot of science in terms of how do we actually get this to the T cells and

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:17.960
again, the right T cells.

00:02:18.040 --> 00:02:19.180
And I don't know the answer to that.

00:02:20.180 --> 00:02:22.480
But this was the in my car trials.

00:02:22.480 --> 00:02:27.540
This is a first in human phase one study that was done in Australia, and it starts with

00:02:27.540 --> 00:02:29.220
6 million to two times.

00:02:29.300 --> 00:02:33.720
It's kind of the seventh, seventh cells per kilogram.

00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:38.760
And again, they had four patients so far, and then they have further dose levels that

00:02:38.760 --> 00:02:41.380
they'll look at and expansion cohorts that we'll look at as well.

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:43.540
So these were not patients at a prior BCMA.

00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:47.820
They were triple class exposed and then adequate organ function.

00:02:47.860 --> 00:02:52.960
And then basically they looked at overall response rate and CAR-T cell expansion and

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:54.660
persistence, which was some cool data.

00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:55.900
Okay.

00:02:55.900 --> 00:02:56.920
So these were the four patients.

00:02:57.480 --> 00:02:59.240
So again, most of the patients were in that.

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:05.800
One patient got the dose level one and then dose level minus one one for these folks.

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:10.400
And again, all of them are refractory to at least a doublet, but potentially triple class

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:10.960
refractory.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:15.860
You can see they had some high risk set of genetics, and we had patients from 61 to 72.

00:03:16.160 --> 00:03:21.560
So a little bit older, but in general, everyone had ECOG performance status.

00:03:21.780 --> 00:03:24.380
So most of these patients had three to five lines of therapy.

00:03:24.700 --> 00:03:28.160
And I think every single one of them, because it is Australia, had prior auto transplant,

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:29.120
which again.

00:03:29.260 --> 00:03:31.060
And might be different if this was in the US.

00:03:31.540 --> 00:03:35.720
So here's some of their translational data in terms of what happened.

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:38.960
So, you know, this question about absolute lymphocyte count, are we seeing it in the

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:39.860
blood and myeloma?

00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:42.080
You know, some of our CAR Ts do, some don't.

00:03:42.220 --> 00:03:42.640
Here we did.

00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:46.420
So there was at least one patient that really, you know, that third week.

00:03:46.540 --> 00:03:48.420
So the expansion happens later, right?

00:03:48.420 --> 00:03:51.940
Because again, you're not taking a whole bunch of cells you've made, put them into a patient

00:03:51.940 --> 00:03:55.180
and, you know, wait for that CAR to really kill right away.

00:03:55.820 --> 00:03:59.240
You're putting in the transgene, which then has to find the T cells, which are the transgene.

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:01.120
Which then starts growing those T cells.

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:04.540
So again, most of the expansion happens in that third to fourth week.

00:04:04.540 --> 00:04:05.540
And that's where you see it.

00:04:05.540 --> 00:04:09.140
And again, most of these were CAR positive cells for a lot of these patients.

00:04:09.140 --> 00:04:14.040
So I think one of these studies will show, one of the slides will show sort of the safety

00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:15.580
piece of that.

00:04:15.580 --> 00:04:20.800
So again, what they're able to show that they did have persistent memory CAR-T cells in

00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:24.680
terms of the types of cells that they were able to see.

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:29.220
And for time, I will skip that, but you'll see the slides and then again, most of these

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:30.220
patients have responded.

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:35.040
So it's 100% response rate and they are still all ongoing in terms of their response.

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:41.180
One had reached CR, the rest for PR, but likely will hopefully have improved results long

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:42.180
term.

00:04:42.180 --> 00:04:45.780
And then you can see that soluble BCMA question that came up earlier that yes, when patients

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:47.520
have active disease, we see it.

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:51.280
And for all four patients that started decreasing once they were responding.

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:56.100
So again, safety, what was really surprising was there was no ICANNs or delayed neurotoxin

00:04:56.100 --> 00:04:59.200
again for patients, but even their CRS was grade one, two.

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:00.200
So again, that's a little bit of a surprise.

